1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,070
Why do we wrangle data?

2
00:00:02,070 --> 00:00:04,530
Data is everywhere in the world offering

3
00:00:04,530 --> 00:00:08,850
invaluable insights such as daily step counts for fitness app developers,

4
00:00:08,850 --> 00:00:11,475
website engagement metrics for marketers,

5
00:00:11,475 --> 00:00:15,315
and national health data for governments to address health crises.

6
00:00:15,315 --> 00:00:20,295
All of them are examples of transforming raw information into actionable knowledge.

7
00:00:20,295 --> 00:00:23,865
One of the first steps to making sense of data is gathering it.

8
00:00:23,865 --> 00:00:28,940
Meaningful data that you can use right away is often hard to find in the real world.

9
00:00:28,940 --> 00:00:34,560
You need to obtain and extract data so it can then be assessed for issues and cleaned.

10
00:00:34,560 --> 00:00:38,860
Then you can finally start to answer questions with the clean data.

11
00:00:38,860 --> 00:00:42,150
Sometimes we may gather data right from the source,

12
00:00:42,150 --> 00:00:44,600
like gathering logs in the smartwatch in order to

13
00:00:44,600 --> 00:00:47,780
figure out how many steps that we've been walking through out the day.

14
00:00:47,780 --> 00:00:50,600
Other times data is provided to us, for example,

15
00:00:50,600 --> 00:00:56,105
by the US Census Bureau or a state's health departments services portal.

16
00:00:56,105 --> 00:00:58,010
We can use this information then to make

17
00:00:58,010 --> 00:01:01,990
reliable conclusions regarding data and answer some interesting questions.

18
00:01:01,990 --> 00:01:05,690
One of the most exciting things about data wrangling is the breadth of techniques that we

19
00:01:05,690 --> 00:01:09,740
can use to be able to gather this data and to put it into actual code.

20
00:01:09,740 --> 00:01:12,950
We've talked about how gathering is the first step towards data

21
00:01:12,950 --> 00:01:16,670
wrangling and ultimately unlocking valuable insights from your data.

22
00:01:16,670 --> 00:01:20,375
There are two key aspects of data gathering techniques.

23
00:01:20,375 --> 00:01:23,150
One, the first step of data gathering is

24
00:01:23,150 --> 00:01:26,435
obtaining data from different sources, like from APIs.

25
00:01:26,435 --> 00:01:29,240
For example, imagine an organization that's

26
00:01:29,240 --> 00:01:32,030
looking to analyze user groups for market insights.

27
00:01:32,030 --> 00:01:34,145
They need data on competitors,

28
00:01:34,145 --> 00:01:36,855
customer interests, pricing, and more.

29
00:01:36,855 --> 00:01:41,620
We can't expect all this data to come from one neatly formatted source.

30
00:01:41,620 --> 00:01:44,855
Then the second step is extracting the obtained data,

31
00:01:44,855 --> 00:01:51,325
such as from.TXT and.CSV files into a format suitable for assessment and cleaning.

32
00:01:51,325 --> 00:01:55,250
After that, we can then use this data to answer questions like

33
00:01:55,250 --> 00:02:00,870
identifying top market opportunities for our hypothetical organization to invest in.

